data.text:
The London wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Prince Philip of Greece in November 1947 led to one of the largest gatherings of European royalty. Standing in the back row of one of the official photographs is Prince Michel of Bourbon-Parma, a kinsman of the groom.

Only months earlier Bourbon had been languishing in a prison camp in French Indo-China (Vietnam), having parachuted into the country with French forces on August 28, 1945.

The previous year he had done much the same with American forces behind enemy lines in Nazi-occupied France as part of Operation Jedburgh. There he sabotaged German military vehicles, planted explosives on trains and learnt to rig a lavatory so that it would blow up when flushed by the enemy.
